## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests analyzed — 0 are effective.** This is a textbook **coverage-touching** suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called exactly once, inflating coverage to ~95%, but almost nothing is verified. A bug in any method (wrong price calculation, returning the wrong product, corrupted CSV) would pass every test.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| Critical | 8 |
| High | 0 |
| Medium | 2 |
| Low | 0 |

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic — entire test class)

**Lines 17–89.** All 10 tests follow the same pattern: call a method, maybe `Assert.IsNotNull`, move on. This is the exact anti-pattern the user suspected. The suite exists to satisfy a coverage gate, not to catch bugs.

---

#### 2. No Assertions — 5 tests (fire-and-forget)

These tests will pass even if the underlying method silently does nothing:

| Test | Line | What's missing |
|------|------|----------------|
| `AddProduct_Works` | 17–21 | Never verifies the product was actually stored |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` | 31–36 | Never verifies the price changed to 14.99 |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` | 38–43 | Never verifies the product is gone |
| `GetProductCount_Works` | 62–66 | Doesn't even capture the return value in a variable — the count is discarded |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` | 84–88 | Never verifies that imported products exist in the catalog |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | 68–74 | Never verifies prices were reduced |

**Example fix — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17):**

```csharp
// BEFORE — proves nothing
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_Works()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
}

// AFTER — verifies the product is retrievable with correct data
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_StoresProductRetrievableBySku()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);

    var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", retrieved?.Sku);
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
}
```

**Example fix — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 31):**

```csharp
// BEFORE — calls UpdatePrice, never checks
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_Works()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
}

// AFTER — verifies the price actually changed
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_UpdatesStoredPrice()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
